/private/tmp/tm_1nkUNAx9xbc.txt:1:An anamorphic image just looks like a movie to me. The flares, the wide frame, the dreamy oval bokeh that makes everything feel expensive. I love it. And it's basically a format that was popularized because studios needed to compete with television. So, we're going to hit a bit of that history, but mostly we're going to be looking at what the squeeze actually does to your image and why true anamorphic gives you something a crop on your 16:9 frame just can't. And stick around to the end, there's something I want to tell you about that will get you to finally finish your short film and pitch a feature to people who've actually made them. Here's a basic shot on a spherical lens, which spherical is what most things are shot on. Nothing different happening, the world looks like the world. Now, here's that same setup on anamorphic. It's stretched vertically with the lens cramming in a wide image to fill my sensor. So, we need to unsqueeze this in post. In Premiere, I'll just right click, go to modify interpret footage, then under pixel aspect ratio, I'll select conform to 1.5 since I'm using these DZO Arcan anamorphic lenses, which are 1.5 times squeeze. Now, with the image stretched out, we have this wide cinematic frame that just feels like a movie. And that's the magic of an anamorphic lens for me. The character it brings, the way it makes you feel like it's another world. For me personally, I want my lens to make my image feel like I'm looking through some magic orb to another dimension, not a window to my backyard. Of course, not all the time. It does depend on what I'm making, but when it comes to narrative work, that's usually the case for me personally. But, what's giving it that feeling? Anamorphic didn't come to film because somebody wanted sexy flares. In the 1950s, TV was killing theaters and studios needed a bigger, wider image without inventing a whole new film format. This &gt;&gt; is Cinerama. &gt;&gt; So, they used this lens trick to squeeze a super wide picture onto the same 35 mm frame, then unsqueezed it in the theater with another specialized lens. All the flares, bokeh, and distortion we're obsessed with now are just side effects of that hack. &gt;&gt; We got it. &gt;&gt; Yeah! &gt;&gt; [cheering] &gt;&gt; Let's look at the tasty treats anamorphic is giving my image. And of course, not all anamorphic are the same. Some have more character, some have less. Imperfections or not, warping or not, flares or barely. And we're looking at just one specific set today, which again, these are the DZO Arcona lenses. DZO sent these and are our partner today. But as always, I don't say anything I don't 100% stand behind. And I was very excited to partner with them on this because I love these lenses a lot. I had the 32, 45, and 75 mm lenses. And like I said before, these are 1.5 squeeze anamorphic lenses. But they have a 1.33 elliptical aperture design, which gives the effect of a two times anamorphic lens, mostly in the bokeh. And I'm going to be putting them up against my DZO spherical cinema lenses so we can see those differences clearly. The first and most obvious thing anamorphic is giving you is that deliciously wide frame. And yes, you can take a spherical shot and crop giving you the same composition, but none of the character. For instance, here's the shot with my spherical 40 mm lens filmed in 16:9 then cropped to 2:35. And here's that same shot with my 45 mm anamorphic lens. These Arcona lenses, again, are that 1.5 squeeze. So I'm shooting open gate on my Pixis 12K, which is basically a 3:2 sensor, just a hair wider. So when we de-squeeze, that gives us a frame of around 2:29:1. So I'll adjust my spherical crop to match and we can see the difference in these lenses from character alone. The most obvious and immediate difference between these two is the extra real estate I'm getting on the sides here. So while my spherical lens is 5 mm wider on the vertical, the 45 mm anamorphic lens is around a 30 mm equivalent on the horizontal field of view with the 1.5 squeeze on it. So, I can move in and get the same framing while feeling the world around him a lot more. And interestingly, if we look at another shot like this one here, I have the 32-mm Arcona anamorphic and the 21-mm spherical. And again, since I have that squeeze on the anamorphic, the horizontal field of view is around 21-mm for that 32-mm. So, now my horizontal framing is matching. And I'll crop and zoom a touch to make the rest match as well. And you can see there's a lot of difference between the lenses here. How they're handling light and bokeh. The anamorphic has more of a vignette, and to me, the anamorphic is feeling more three-dimensional overall. And this is the case when I compare my 75-mm anamorphic to the 40 spherical as well, or the 32 anamorphic to the 40 spherical. Each time, I'm feeling the subject more separated. And that's partly due to the vignetting and distortion I'm getting in these lenses. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; With a spherical lens, you're often getting straight lines like the edge of a wall or door frame. But with the anamorphic, we're starting to bend the world on the edges. And we can see that most clearly with the widest anamorphic lens in the kit. So, let's look at this shot here with the fence in the back on a spherical lens. We have all straight lines. But when I switch to my 32-mm anamorphic, you can see how much distortion we're getting with the edges bowing out. Of course, like any set of lenses, this varies across the focal lengths. And we have it most pronounced on the widest lens. But as we move to the 45, it drops quite a bit. And the 75-mm is very slight. And like we talked about before, the 32-mm anamorphic is that 21-mm equivalent horizontally. So, it is feeling more like a wide-angle lens like you have with this 21 spherical. So, as we move to the edges of both, you are getting distortion with either one. And like I just showed, distortion isn't only in anamorphic lenses, but most anamorphic lenses do tend to have distortion that I find extra pleasing. It's one of the main ingredients of what I keep calling character. I tend to get bummed out when an anamorphic lens has very little of it. Since again, that distortion is a big reason why I'm getting that shift in how the space is rendered. And often, it's feeling more separated and alive for me. And I'm personally loving the distortion in these Arcona lenses. Next, we're going to talk Boca, but before we do, as promised, let's talk about pitching your feature idea. Another partner of ours, Film Fest Knoxville has an international film festival in Knoxville, Tennessee, November 12th through the 15th, and it's legit. MovieMaker named it one of the 50 festivals actually worth the entry fee. But, what I want you to know about it is the elevator pitch. You and your team make an 8-minute proof-of-concept short film, plus a 1-minute pitch for a feature. So, right out of the gate, it forces you to do the hardest part, make the idea real. Then, an independent committee picks the top eight. Those eight get screened in front of a live audience and a jury of working industry pros. Then, you pitch your feature live on the spot and take their questions. Top three teams win cash and get into the elevator development lab run this year by 10 Acre Films, producers behind over 20 features, 10 of them at Sundance, including Sorry to Bother You. And let's be real, the odds of you getting a feature out of this are as slim as they are when you have an agent and you're pitching features out in Hollywood. I know that world firsthand. But, that's not the reason here for me. The real value to something like this, in my opinion, is the community that you're taking part in, the motivation it gives you, and the practice you'll be getting pitching it. If there's one thing I've learned over the last 8 years of pitching, it's that the friendships you make will drive you closer to your goal than anything else. So, that's the real pitch. And it doesn't hurt that you get on the radar of people who can actually help make it happen. Registration closes July 16th. It's 80 bucks per team. It includes a full festival pass, and your finished film is due October 17th. So, grab a a friends, pick that idea that won't leave you alone, and go for it. Link in the description, or head to filmfestknox.com. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; One of the absolute best aspects of an anamorphic lens is the bokeh, and not just in the very obvious places, like with the points of light here, but in every shot. Compared to a spherical lens, you get this streaking whirly blur that feels cinematic, versus a blooming blur that feels more photographic, at least to me. Both are great, just different. Again, that's going to be the most pronounced in points of light like this here. In the spherical, we're getting circles of light, while in the anamorphic, it's stretching those points to that oval shape. And if we look at it in things like leaves and branches, like you see here, you can see how much it's doing to the edges to really infuse that character. You're also getting some lens breathing here as you rack focus, which feels very classic cinema to me. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Probably the most famous aspect of an anamorphic lens is the lens flare, which is funny, because while I do love lens flares, it's not at the top of my list of why I love anamorphic. When people talk about lens flares now, they think JJ Abrams, but the films of the '80s and '90s have some of the best examples of lens flares overall, in my opinion. And we are getting great flares with these lenses. The Arcanas have a white coating design, which means the flare will take on the color of the light source. This is a big plus, since it feels more natural to the image overall, and that flare is going to vary across the size of the source, as well as where it's positioned in frame. As we move the light around, we're getting a lot of life in the flare moving along with it. And as we adjust our T-stop, the flare is going to look a bit different as well, and we can also ping the lens from outside of the frame to get different looks like you see here for all kinds of styles. And you can see how the flare is moving across the glass on the front here, as well, which doesn't matter, but it looks cool. Another perk, especially with the Arcanas 1.5 squeeze, is that we can shift between aspect ratios in camera to adjust how wide our final frame is. With 3:2, you're landing at around 2:2:1. If I switch to 16:9, that same 1.5 squeeze takes us to around 2.66:1. 17:9 on my Pixis takes us to 2.8:1. And if I go to 6:5, I'm landing around 1.8:1, which is basically 16:9. So, if you want, you can stay with a 16:9 frame while still getting all the character of the anamorphic lens. Which for me, this is perfect for talking head type shots like we're doing right here. It just feels elevated to me. It stands out because people aren't used to seeing anamorphic this way. I also have these adapters here, so I can go PL to RF and pop these on my Canon C50, which we will be talking about soon. Or even better, I can use an adapter to pair these with my Ronin 4D. Since these lenses are so small and light, there's no issues with balancing on the head here. And now I'm getting the smoothness of the 4D with the epic look of the anamorphic. And with my LiDAR on here, I'll have autofocus as well, giving me maybe the coolest setup that we've used on the show yet. Overall, these lenses are cleanish budget anamorphic, but thankfully not too clean that they are void of character. Since, as you can see, they are oozing with it. They're also sharp even when wide open, but without that digital harshness. So, they're helping curb that clinical look overall, too. Which is another big plus to anamorphic lenses. We have links to these in the notes below. And if you use our link, you can get 5% off these Arcan lenses or any other lenses on the DZOptics store. And what do you think? Are you a fan of anamorphic like me, or do you prefer the look of spherical? Let us know in the comments below. And if you haven't seen it, we have a whole new show and channel called Page One, where Justin breaks down the scripts of different films. We just released a new episode on Take Shelter, but there's also episodes on The Prestige, Monsters Inc., and Nosferatu. So, check all that in the links as well. And until next time, don't forget to write, shoot, edit, repeat. &gt;&gt; [music] [music] &gt;&gt; I'll see you later. Ta-ta.
/private/tmp/tm_LDfPPvjqY9k.txt:1:Transporting gear is a pain. Whether that's around a studio or a location, so we're going to look at a simple piece of gear that solves that issue and how you can turn it into a mobile lighting and workstation. This is the SmallRig 36-in lightweight camera cart, which we're going to turn into an all-in-one filmmaking tool. Why? Your scientists were so preoccupied with whether or not they could, they didn't stop to think if they should. The actual function of a camera cart like this is just to carry your gear, which sounds boring and it is, but it's also an insanely helpful and unsung hero on set. A cart like this is large enough to pack most everything you'd take to a small shoot in just one cart and away you go. Then once you're staged, you turn it into a mobile table of the most important consistently used gear, like we did here while shooting for next week's episode. And comment what shot you think we're recreating below. The best wrong answer gets pinned to the top. Anyway, it comes like this here, but is an easy 3-minute toolless assembly and disassembly. And at 61 lb, it's easy to just toss in any car. And lightweight doesn't mean it can't carry. Wait, you have a load capacity of 551 lb. So like I said before, I can use it for more than just transporting gear. Like since it's a camera cart, we can put a camera on it. Use it like a makeshift dolly of sorts. At first, I put my Pixis on there with a high hat and it did work a bit if we had it on a very smooth surface. So you could use it as a dolly in a pinch, but overall, it was too bumpy to be useful in most cases, which might be dumb to even talk about, but I don't care. I'm squeezing every bit of juice out of this juice box. There's something about that guy's tone of voice I don't like. &gt;&gt; Plus, I have the Ronin 4D, so I could pop that on to smooth everything out and genuinely use it like a dolly, but I'll get back to that. With it being able to handle 551 lb, I could put a person on it. So I had Justin sit on the front to get this trippy almost Spike Lee style shot or maybe he popped too many Flintstones vitamins. Yeah, I don't hear them chatting the noise. Move too quick, can't stop for the talking. I hear them chatting with the boys. Not so tough, but noise keep walking. Yeah, just too sharp with the pies. White girls want to tell me I'm awesome, yeah. Hot like fire on the pan. If you want to touch me, please use caution. &gt;&gt; Or maybe he's just enjoying a delightful bike ride. Another idea that has nothing to do with the use of a camera cart that popped into my head was walking talks. A walking talk is exactly what it sounds like. It's a shot with characters having a conversation while in motion, and the camera is following along with them. While doing this, you'll have the camera operator following along with a boom operator and maybe someone Hollywooding a bounce flag or light, which to Hollywood something just means a crew member is holding a piece of gear that would normally be rigged. But you have these baby pins on the four corners of the cart, so I decided to see if I could rig this out. So, I popped one of those baby pins out in the front and put a C-stand body in, then a C-stand arm on the baby pin on the other side. And now I can mount a flag on the one C-stand and a light on the arm and a boom mic on the body of the C-stand as well. And now we have this. Yuck. Which looks ridiculous, but I do have a mobile walking talk rig. And again, since I have my Ronin 4D, I can use that to stabilize the image and clean up any bumps to give us a solid walking talk where I can do the job of four people all by myself. And again, this looks absolutely ridiculous. We did use some of our scrap gear for testing this out, but this works really well. So, when we rig it out properly, it'll look fine on set, too. You also have the handle here that can pop off and be another riser to mount monitors or other bits of gear. And obviously, building out a camera cart for a walking talk isn't something you would do when you have a production budget, but I come from the school of DIY filmmaking, so I can't stop my mind from wandering back. And if you're a one-person filmmaking team, there you go. What I could definitely see me using it for is just as a mobile production station. Pop a light on and a mic and be able to move easily where there's very little crew. Different setups in different areas of a location while reducing the number of stands you need to set up and move. If you're dealing with little to no crew, something like this can be a lifesaver. Or you could put a light on the cart and use the cart to move that light around to get different effects like we did here. But again, the main use for this is carrying your Whatever you want to put on it. Just pile it on and away you go. You have these soft pads here, too, so you can stage your lenses when you shift over to shooting mode. You also have a ton of mounting options around the cart for whatever you would need and a detachable side panel to convert into a workbench like we showed before. At the bottom, we have 8-in pneumatic shock absorbing casters that can roll over anything. Grass, concrete, rocks, small steps, ducks, feet. And is the reason some of these shots went on smooth flooring actually work pretty well. And of course, you can lock these. My one complaint so far is that these pieces where I mount the wheels when packing back up stick out and take up storage space on the bottom. So, there is that. But other than that, I love this thing. We're getting along great so far. Once you're all done with it, it packs up nicely with its removable casters and handrail making it very easy to transport and it's airline oversize compliant meeting most airline standards, so it's travel ready, too. So, as I said in the beginning, this type of gear sounds boring, but it can be the most versatile and headache releasing tool for your production. Of course, camera carts can be pretty pricey. So, if you don't have the budget for it, you could get started with something simple from a local hardware store. You won't be able to do all the stuff we showed in this episode, but any kind of cart to help transport your gear on location is going to be a big win. But that's it for today. Big thank you to SmallRig for sending the cart and sponsoring the episode. If you want to check out the cart for yourself, you can get that online or in some physical stores. Links below for all of that. And until next time, don't forget to write, shoot, edit, repeat. See you later. Ta-ta.

